  "nursesNote": "These are disruptive behavior disorders of childhood and adolescence. Oppositional defiant disorder (ODD) is a pattern of angry or irritable mood and argumentative, defiant behavior toward authority figures, sometimes with vindictiveness, but without seriously violating the basic rights of others. Conduct disorder is more serious and involves repeatedly violating the rights of others or major rules: aggression toward people or animals, destruction of property, deceit or theft, and serious rule-breaking; it can progress to antisocial personality disorder, so early help matters. The nurse uses firm, clear, consistent limits with predictable consequences and follows through (no empty threats), reinforces positive behavior with praise and behavior contracts, maintains a structured routine, watches for aggression to protect safety, and supports therapy and parent training.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Set firm, clear, consistent limits",
    "Apply predictable consequences and follow through",
    "Reinforce positive behavior with praise and contracts",
    "Maintain safety and watch for aggression",
    "Support therapy and parent training"
  ],
